INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (5,1,'2020-03-12 12:30:04','2020-03-12 12:30:04','[[\"Title\",\"Descriptions\",\"\"],[\"Birds\",\"We have 112 birds, including breeding Ospreys\",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=63\\\">Find out more</a>\"],[\"Mammals\",\"We have 24 mammals, including dormouse!\",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=385\\\">Find out more</a>\"],[\"Fish\",\"We have lots of fresh water fish around our reserves.\",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=388\\\">Find out more</a>\"],[\"Reptiles\",\"We have 6 official reptiles that you can find over our reserves \",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=390\\\">Find out more</a>\"],[\"Amphibians\",\"We have 6 official amphibians that you can find over our reserves \",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=392\\\">Find out more</a>\"],[\"Invertebrates\",\"We have 504 moths,18 dragonflies & damselflies\",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=394\\\">Find out more</a>\"],[\"Plants\",\"There are Wildflowers, Ferns and horsetails as well as grasses, sedges and rushes.\",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=398\\\">Find out more</a>\"],[\"Other\",\"This is where any extra things that don\'t fit into the other categories can be found.\",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=396\\\">Find out more</a>\"]]','Wildlife Categories','If you would like to edit description please type into appropriate cell below in column B and click save changes.\n','publish','closed','closed','','wildlife-categorises','','','2020-04-15 14:32:08','2020-04-15 13:32:08','',0,'http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?post_type=tablepress_table&#038;p=5',0,'tablepress_table','application/json',0),(8,1,'2020-03-12 15:32:20','2020-03-12 15:32:20','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>[google_map_easy id=\"1\" enable_full_screen_btn=\"0\" ]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Map','','publish','closed','closed','','home','','','2020-04-14 17:26:31','2020-04-14 16:26:31','',0,'http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=8',0,'page','',0),(11,1,'2020-03-12 13:21:01','2020-03-12 13:21:01','[[\"ID\",\"Photo\",\"Name\",\"Brief Description\",\"Category \",\"Individual Page on site\",\"Full Description \",\"View Full Information\",\"Photo (lrg)\"],[\"1\",\"<img src=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/low-angle-photography-of-flock-of-flying-birds-1386454-1-1.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"Osprey Birds\\\" width=\\\"200\\\" height=\\\"200\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-full wp-image-79\\\" />\",\"Osprey\",\"The main attraction of Dyfi Wildlife Centre\",\"Birds\",\"Yes\",\"Ospreys are large majestic birds of prey with a fascinating ecology and an incredible watch-ability!\\n\\nA century ago ospreys in the UK were hunted to extinction. Forty years later they began to make a come back and since then we have learnt a lot more about them by studying rather than shooting them. The more we learn about this amazing species the more tools we have in the tool box to help them recover from world wide declines.\",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=129\\\">More</a>\",\"<img src=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/low-angle-photography-of-flock-of-flying-birds-1386454-1-1.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"Osprey Birds\\\" width=\\\"400\\\" height=\\\"400\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-full wp-image-79\\\" />\"],[\"2\",\"\",\"Jay\",\"Scientific name: Garrulus glandarius\\n\\nThe jay is a colourful member of the crow family, with brilliant blue wing patches. It is famous for searching out acorns in autumnal woodlands and parks, often storing them for the winter ahead.\",\"Birds\",\"\",\"\",\"\",\"\"],[\"3\",\"<img src=\\\"https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2019/10/20/14/49/animal-4563886_960_720.jpg\\\" width=\\\"200\\\" height=\\\"200\\\" alt=\\\"picture of a robin red breast\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-medium\\\" />\",\"Robin\",\"\",\"Birds\",\"\",\"\",\"\",\"\"],[\"4\",\"\",\"Common Lizard\",\"Look out for a common lizard basking in the warm sun as you wander around heathlands, moorlands and grasslands. You might even be lucky enough to spot one in your garden, too!\",\"Reptiles\",\"\",\"\",\"\",\"\"],[\"5\",\"<img src=\\\"https://c.pxhere.com/images/bf/5c/d3a8d6001bee62900a0b2d22d1ec-1601628.jpg!d\\\" width=\\\"200\\\" height=\\\"200\\\" alt=\\\"marsh violets picture, purple\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-medium\\\" />\",\"Marsh Violets\",\"As its name suggests, the Marsh violet likes damp spots, such as marshes, bogs and wet woods. It is a low-growing plant with kidney-shaped leaves and pale lilac flowers.\",\"Plants\",\"\",\"\",\"\",\"\"],[\"6\",\"<img src=\\\"https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2016/03/22/01/02/common-toad-1272014_960_720.jpg\\\" width=\\\"200\\\" height=\\\"200\\\" alt=\\\"picture of common toad, green\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-medium\\\" />\",\"Common Toad\",\"Despite its warts and ancient associations with witches, the common toad is a gardener\'s friend, sucking up slugs and snails. It is famous for migrating en masse to its breeding ponds.\",\"Amphibians\",\"Yes\",\"Common toads are amphibians, breeding in ponds during the spring and spending much of the rest of the year feeding in woodland, gardens, hedgerows and tussocky grassland. They are famous for their mass migrations back to their breeding ponds on the first warm, damp evenings of the year, often around St. Valentine\'s Day. Common toads tend to breed in larger, deeper ponds than common frogs, but still frequent gardens. They hibernate over winter, often under log piles, stones or even in old flower pots!\",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=491\\\">More</a>\",\"<img src=\\\"https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2016/03/22/01/02/common-toad-1272014_960_720.jpg\\\" width=\\\"400\\\" height=\\\"400\\\" alt=\\\"picture of common toad, green\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-medium\\\" />\"],[\"7\",\"\",\"Barn Owl\",\"With heart-shaped face, buff back and wings and pure white underparts, the barn owl is a distinctive and much-loved countryside bird.\",\"Birds\",\"\",\"\",\"\",\"\"],[\"8\",\"\",\"Beaver\",\"A water and on land creature\",\"Mammals\",\"\",\"\",\"\",\"\"],[\"9\",\"<img src=\\\"https://www.montwt.co.uk/sites/default/files/styles/node_hero_desk_wide/public/2018-05/Male%20Adonis%20Blue%20Colin%20Williams%2001062014.JPG?h=e982d60e&itok=E42vgF_q\\\" width=\\\"200\\\" height=\\\"300\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-medium\\\" />\",\"Adonis blue\",\"The rare Adonis blue can be spotted on sunny chalk grasslands throughout summer. Males are a dazzling sky-blue in colour, while females are duller brown.\",\"Invertebrates\",\"No\",\"\",\"\",\"\"],[\"10\",\"<img src=\\\"https://www.montwt.co.uk/sites/default/files/styles/grid_teaser/public/2018-01/Chub%20%28c%29%20Jack%20Perks.jpg?h=52409af7&itok=wsPNlBy2\\\" width=\\\"200\\\" height=\\\"200\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-medium\\\" />\",\"Chub\",\"The silvery chub can be seen gathering in large shoals in lowland rivers and streams. It is a member of the carp family and looks very similar to the dace, but is larger and has redder fins. A freshwater fish\",\"Fish\",\"No\",\"\",\"\",\"\"],[\"11\",\"<img src=\\\"https://www.montwt.co.uk/sites/default/files/styles/grid_teaser/public/2018-01/MHA_08_020711_1097.jpg?h=59f9d53c&itok=5x2aACtb\\\" width=\\\"200\\\" height=\\\"200\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-medium\\\" />\",\"Sphagnum Moss\",\"Sphagnum Mosses carpet the ground with colour on our marshes, heaths and moors. They play a vital role in the creation of peat bogs: by storing water in their spongy forms, they prevent the decay of dead plant material and eventually form peat.\",\"Other\",\"Yes\",\"Sphagnum Mosses carpet the ground with colour on our marshes, heaths and moors. They play a vital role in the creation of peat bogs: by storing water in their spongy forms, they prevent the decay of dead plant material and eventually form peat. There are at least ten species of Sphagnum Moss in the UK, which are very difficult to tell apart. These species range in colour from red and pink, to orange and green. Sphagnum Moss plants are very small, but they grow closely together, forming spongy carpets; \'hummocks\' are even created when the mosses grow to form large mounds up to a metre high.\",\"<a href=\\\"http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?page_id=538\\\">More</a>\",\"<img src=\\\"https://www.montwt.co.uk/sites/default/files/styles/grid_teaser/public/2018-01/MHA_08_020711_1097.jpg?h=59f9d53c&itok=5x2aACtb\\\" width=\\\"400\\\" height=\\\"400\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-medium\\\" />\"],[\"12\",\"<img src=\\\"https://thenypost.files.wordpress.com/2018/07/drunk-seaguls-england.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&w=915\\\" width=\\\"200\\\" height=\\\"200\\\" class=\\\"alignnone size-medium\\\" />\",\"Seagulls\",\"Gulls or seagulls are seabirds of the family Laridae in the suborder Lari. They are most closely related to the terns (family Sternidae) and only distantly related to auks, skimmers, and more distantly to the waders.\",\"Birds\",\"No\",\"\",\"\",\"\"]]','Wildlfie','To edit you may change columns C,D,G. Once edited click save changes.\nTo delete check rows wanting to delete and click delete rows and then save changes.\nFor edits to any of the other columns, make note and go to admin dashboard and e-mail with requests, adding photos to the media section where possible. ','publish','closed','closed','','wildlfie','','','2020-04-17 15:27:22','2020-04-17 14:27:22','',0,'http://users.aber.ac.uk/ydw/dyfiwildlifecentre/?post_type=tablepress_table&#038;p=11',0,'tablepress_table','application/json',0),(21,1,'2020-03-12 16:10:44','2020-03-12 16:10:44','','polylang_mo_2','','private','closed','closed','','polylang_mo_2','','','2020-03-12 16:10: